Introduction

Clustering and dimension reduction can be used in various ways, in several combinations; however, there are some field for which the clustering studies are not applicable. certain market or field specific dynamics do not allow us to perform USL studies based on the market specific factors. The clustering studies are numerous for understanding market segmentation and understanding consumer base. I have tried to create such a study based on viewership of certain movies across several cities in world. I expect to see some interesting insights from the study.

As an aim of this exercise, I intend to cluster the dataset of movie sales according to the expected observation of seasonality of sale of movie tickets, or observation of different amount of sales. ### Loading the necessary libraries

library(factoextra)

data <- read.csv("cinemaTicket_Ref.csv")

About the dataset

The dataset includes 1 film_code - this is the Movie identifier

2 city - the city where the movie was screened

3 tickets_sold - total tickets sold

4 tickets_out - total tickets not sold

5 show_time - run time of a particular movie

6 occu_perc - percentage measure of occupancy

7 ticket_price - price of the ticket indonesian

8 ticket_use - how many tickets were used

9 capacity - capacity of the cinema in one screening

10 date

11 month

12 quarter

13 day

14 total_sales - total sales made for a movie in particular screening

The plot clearly shows that there are some variables which are correlated with some other variables in the dataset. This means we can use some dimension reduction techniques for easy computation of the analysis.

The existance of such correlted variables in the dataset on which the clustering will be done will make the results rather skewed and make process unnecessarily complicated. For example Ticked used has high correlation with tickets sold -> Meaning that most of the people who buy the tickets actually do use them. We will remove the tickets used column later

The other correlation is as expected, between the sales and sold tickets. This could be eliminated, but We can see their importance later

Principal Component Analysis(PCA)

Finding optimal number of components

pca <- prcomp(data[,-1], center=TRUE, scale=TRUE)

fviz_eig(pca)

summary(pca)

Lets now check the eigen values of the correlation.

eigen(cor(data[-1]))$values
##  [1]  2.593704e+00  2.101049e+00  1.926795e+00  1.598042e+00  1.002911e+00
##  [6]  9.181299e-01  4.454957e-01  3.068999e-01  1.067352e-01  2.398610e-04
## [11] -2.050952e-16
fviz_eig(pca, choice='eigenvalue')

Looking at the results above and also by the Scree-plot, it becomes clear that there are 5 variables with an eigen value of more than 1. As a general thumb rule, it is a good practice to select those variables which has eigen value of 1 or more. This means the first five variables will be good for further analysis.

Component analysis

Here we analyze the PCA of the variables from the perspective of the below graph

variablepca <- get_pca_var(pca)
options(ggrepel.max.overlaps = Inf)    # increasing the overlap capacity
fviz_pca_var(pca, col.var="cos2", alpha.var="contrib", 
             gradient.cols = c("blue", "green", "red"), repel = TRUE)

Checking the contribution of each variable

fviz_contrib(pca, choice = "var", axes = 1:5)

Here we also see that there are some variables which are not crucial in explaining the contribution to PCA. so we can remove those components. Additionally we also remove Tickets sold column, as it had high correlation with sales and is shown here as one of the most important column. we still keep show time. As it is one of the important features of any movie. People form their recommendations based on that.

Clustering of the dataset

Checking the clustering tendancy of the dataset

names(finaldata)
##  [1] "city"         "show_time"    "occu_perc"    "ticket_price" "ticket_use"  
##  [6] "capacity"     "month"        "quarter"      "day"          "total_sales"
finaldata<-finaldata[,2:10]
clusterable <- get_clust_tendency(finaldata, n = nrow(finaldata)-1, graph = FALSE)
clusterable$hopkins_stat
## [1] 0.9371886

The above value clearly suggest that the dataset is highly clusterable. However, it could also mean that the data is in homogenous. this is why we hope to at least get 2 clusters in this data. hopkin’s statistic = 0.9473917 is actually very high.

Finding optimal number of clusters

To find optimal number of clusters, different methods would be used to compare and come up with the best result.

Using Silhoutte statistic

f1 <- fviz_nbclust(finaldata, FUNcluster = kmeans, method = "silhouette") + 
  ggtitle("Optimal number of clusters \n K-means")

f2 <- fviz_nbclust(finaldata, FUNcluster = cluster::pam, method = "silhouette") + 
  ggtitle("Optimal number of clusters \n PAM")

grid.arrange(f1, f2, ncol=2)

The above plots suggest that using both K-means and PAM algorithm, 2 clusters would be the best case for this dataset.

Using total Within Sum of Squares of clusters statistics

f3 <- fviz_nbclust(finaldata, FUNcluster = kmeans, method = "wss") + 
  ggtitle("Optimal number of clusters \n K-means")

f4 <- fviz_nbclust(finaldata, FUNcluster = cluster::pam, method = "wss") + 
  ggtitle("Optimal number of clusters \n PAM")

grid.arrange(f3, f4, ncol=2)

Now, this plot is a bit complicated as there is no obvious answer as to how many clusters would be ideal. Visualizing the plot properly, one can argue if 2 or more clusters should be used. although the probabilities of getting meaningful classification in more than 2 clusters is very low, this can be considered.

Using Elbow method

k_max <- 10

wss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(finaldata, k, 
                                          nstart=50,iter.max = 1000 )$tot.withinss})

wss
##  [1] 222898052  77127061  43980353  20390561  29430301  10895441   9852586
##  [8]   9037770   7324864   7059948
plot(1:k_max, wss,
     type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
     xlab="Number of clusters K",
     ylab="Total within-clusters sum of squares")

This plot further emphasises that the number of clusters should be 2 for the dataset as the elbow appears at 2.

K-means clustering

Considering 2 clusters

kmean2 <- eclust(finaldata, k=2 , FUNcluster="kmeans", hc_metric="euclidean", graph=F)

cluster2 <- fviz_cluster(kmean2, finaldata, elipse.type="convex", geom=c("point")) + ggtitle("K-means with 2 clusters")

sil2 <- fviz_silhouette(kmean2)
##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1  290          0.86
## 2       2   15          0.55
grid.arrange(cluster2, sil2, ncol=2)

As we can see, the data is highly homogenous. the clustering exercise is not highly useful for this kind of dataset. however considering the 2 clusters, and the above graph, we cannot get more clusters from the above dataset.

The above outputs suggest that the above clustering based on only 2 clusters is a best possible fit for the dataset as the average silhouette width for both the clusters is positive. This means the points in both the clusters are clustered properly. This is ithe conclusion which was reached after having tried several clustering techniques and several clustering methodologies. Those examples are added as an Appendix to the main Dimension Reduction and Clustering exercise above.

The other clusters suggested by the k-means will be tried below:

Appendix

Considering several other clustering exercises after the dimentions are selected above.

Considering 5 clusters

kmean5 <- eclust(finaldata, k=5 , FUNcluster="kmeans", hc_metric="euclidean", graph=F)

cluster5 <- fviz_cluster(kmean5, finaldata, elipse.type="convex", geom=c("point")) + ggtitle("K-means with 5 clusters")

sil5 <- fviz_silhouette(kmean5)

## 3       3   13          0.29

## 5       5   50          0.53

Although some clusters have positive average silhouette width, there exists two clusters with values close to 0(0 and -0.01) suggesting the idea of using 5 clusters not so good. However, let’s analyze the same for 3 clusters.

Considering 3 clusters

kmean3 <- eclust(finaldata, k=3 , FUNcluster="kmeans", hc_metric="euclidean", graph=F)

cluster3 <- fviz_cluster(kmean3, finaldata, elipse.type="convex", geom=c("point")) + ggtitle("K-means with 3 clusters")

sil3 <- fviz_silhouette(kmean3)
##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1  221          0.73
## 2       2   72          0.47
## 3       3   12          0.51
grid.arrange(cluster3, sil3, ncol=2)

The above results and plots clearly suggest that there is some serious overlapping of clusters which is not a great thing. It means out of all these possibilties given by K-means algorithm, classifying the countries into 2 clusters would be the best idea.

Let’s now use PAM algorithm to check what results does it gives.

PAM clustering

Considering 2 clusters

pam2 <- eclust(finaldata, k=2 , FUNcluster="pam", hc_metric="euclidean", graph=F)

cpam2 <- fviz_cluster(pam2, finaldata, elipse.type="convex", geom=c("point")) + ggtitle("PAM with 2 clusters")

silpam2 <- fviz_silhouette(pam2)
##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1  220          0.82
## 2       2   85          0.06
grid.arrange(cpam2, silpam2, ncol=2)

The outputs suggest the same as that of K-means that classifying the nations into 2 clusters would be a good way going forward in the analysis. However, let’s consider other possibilities before concluding anything.

Considering 5 clusters

pam5 <- eclust(finaldata, k=5 , FUNcluster="pam", hc_metric="euclidean", graph=F)

cpam5 <- fviz_cluster(pam5, finaldata, elipse.type="convex", geom=c("point")) + ggtitle("PAM with 5 clusters")

silpam5 <- fviz_silhouette(pam5)

## 2       2   32          0.49
## 3       3   82          0.61
## 4       4   15          0.34
## 5       5   46          0.56

Clearly, the result suggest it is not a bad idea to consider 5 clusters but the presence of overlapping as seen in the plot and also the negative silhouette width for some countries suggest it would be better to consider more options.

Considering 3 clusters

pam3 <- eclust(finaldata, k=3 , FUNcluster="pam", hc_metric="euclidean", graph=F)

cpam3 <- fviz_cluster(pam3, finaldata, elipse.type="convex", geom=c("point")) + ggtitle("PAM with 3 clusters")

silpam3 <- fviz_silhouette(pam3)
##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1  210          0.72
## 2       2   80          0.48
## 3       3   15          0.44
grid.arrange(cpam3, silpam3, ncol=2)

Again, the same issue of overlapping exist in this case. Considering all the options, using 2 clusters seems to be the best option.

Conclusion:

The exercise above suggests that almost all variables namely have the major contributions. This can be accepted as this is movie ticket sales data from 2018 when consumer spending was in full swing.

Apart from this, if I tried to get more clusters from the dataset, then the clusters were operlapping eachother. this is because, as explained, the data is highly homogenous. Even the “PAM with 2 clusters”, is not very useful.

However, since it is a data over the year of 2018, one would have expected a seasonality in terms of the movie sales and some type of clustering or trend.
